## Example 7 — Find Diagonal Lengths

The area of a rhombus is 168 square centimeters. If one diagonal is three times as long as the other, what are the lengths of the diagonals to the nearest tenth of a centimeter?

Let d1 = x and d2 = 3x.
[
A = d1 * d2 / 2
]
[
168 = x * 3x / 2
]
[
168 = 3x^2 / 2
]
[
336 = 3x^2
]
[
x^2 = 112
]
[
x ≈ 10.6
]

So d1 ≈ 10.6 cm and d2 ≈ 31.8 cm.

